post_text:
With schools being allowed to open following specific guidance from the NY State Education Department and the NY State Department of Health, we have made alterations to the school year calendar previously posted. Our staff will be working together on September 2nd, 3rd, 8th and 9th to prepare to welcome students back to campus for the first time since March 16th. Our first instructional day for students will be on Thursday, September 10th. For those who have elected "in-person" instruction, this will be a day for cohort B.

Virtual/remote students will also begin with their classes on September 10th. Our revised calendar reflects changes from September through January. In the event that everyone is not able to return to school for the second semester, additional changes will be made to our school year calendar from February through June at a later time.

http://www.marcellusschools.org/teacherpage.cfm?teacher=3285

post_text:
More good news from our Marcellus family! Recent graduate Kevin Brown was recently awarded a Student Award at the Nazareth College President's Civic Engagement Awards.

Kevin, who achieved the rank of Eagle Scout before attending Nazareth, has worked with their "Alternative Breaks" program exploring the issue of housing and homelessness and plans to continue working with a Rochester-area homeless shelter despite the current shutdown.

You can read more about Kevin, and all the other winners, here: https://www2.naz.edu/index.php?cID=4264

Congratulations, Kevin!

post_text:
Congratulations to SHS senior Quinn Clarke, enrolled in the Outdoor Powersports Equipment program at Cayuga-Onondaga BOCES, for passing six Briggs and Stratton Master Service Technician exams to achieve Master Technician status! Quinn has worked diligently since the shutdown to achieve his goal.

The exams covered Theory and General Knowledge, Diagnostics and Troubleshooting, Engine Systems, Fuel Systems - Carburetor and Electronic Fuel Injection, Failure Analysis and Warranty Decisions, Products - Pressure Washers and Portable Generators. The exams are all considered quite rigorous.

Congratulations to Quinn for his incredible achievement!

Congratulations to SHS senior Quinn Clarke, enrolled in the Outdoor Powersports Equipment program at Cayuga-Onondaga BOCES, for passing six Briggs and Stratton Master Service Technician exams to achieve Master Technician status! Quinn has worked diligently since the shutdown to achieve his goal.

The exams covered Theory and General Knowledge, Diagnostics and Troubleshooting, Engine Systems, Fuel Systems - Carburetor and Electronic Fuel Injection, Failure Analysis and Warranty Decisions, Products - Pressure Washers and Portable Generators. The exams are all considered quite rigorous.

Congratulations to Quinn for his incredible achievement!

UPDATED: The Parents’ Night Out that was postponed by the Feb. 7 snow day has been rescheduled to 6 to 9 p.m. Friday, March 13. All the original details still apply: Games, entertainment and food for students in grades K-6 at Driver Middle School. The cost is $25 in advance ($20 each for two or more children in a family) or $30 at the door. Except now it will be held at Marcellus High School!

Money already paid for the Feb. 7 date can be held as payment for the new date. If students cannot attend March 13, parents can request a refund from jbaker@marcellusschools.org or donate the money to the Class of 2022!

post_text:
Congratulations to Jack Waterman (grade 6) and Connor Combs and Chris Smorol (grade 5) for winning a 🏆 during a Jan. 18 scholastic ♟ tournament at Ed Smith School in Syracuse.

The three are members of the Marcellus Chess Club, which has been meeting twice a month since November under the direction of volunteer adviser and Marcellus substitute teacher Sue Riccardi.

Also, a shout-out to Mrs. Riccardi’s son, 2018 Marcellus graduate Joe Riccardi, who helped out club members while he was home on break recently from the University of Buffalo.

post_text:
Congratulations to the Robo Sapiens, a brand-new First LEGO League team formed this year and led by DMS teacher Audrey Misiano. They won not only the Core Values Award at their first competition in Auburn on Nov. 16, but also first-place overall! Next, they advance to the regional competition in Rochester on Dec. 8. The Robo Sapiens are: Tabor Clark, grade 4; Ben Cook and Geo Misiano, grade 5; Mia Caryl and Soleil Misiano, grade 7; and Jackson Clark, grade 8. Way! To! Go! 🥳👍🏆🎉
Watch here: https://youtu.be/h1gMosXmRJI

post_text: Marcellus educators have been tinkering away inside a "little incubator" of innovation and experimentation to help education catch up with our rapidly changing world. Superintendent Michelle Brantner explains in a new video.
shared_text:
MARCELLUSSCHOOLS.ORG
Superintendent opens dialogue on instructional changes | Marcellus School District
text:
Marcellus educators have been tinkering away inside a "little incubator" of innovation and experimentation to help education catch up with our rapidly changing world. Superintendent Michelle Brantner explains in a new video.

post_text: The countdown to the start of school hasn't *quite* begun (let's at least get to August!), but it's definitely not too early to mark up your calendar with some important start-of-term dates, including the Grand Opening of the newly renovated Marcellus High School on Sept. 7! https://tinyurl.com/y553xe2s

post_text: As of Aug. 1, Marcellus Central School District will be discontinuing its use of School News Notifier (SNN) as a way to push out district and school-level news to subscribers via email. But don’t worry about keeping tabs on what’s happening here on campus. The district still has at its disposal a variety of communication tools -- including this here Facebook page! -- to share information about the district and our schools.

post_text: Parents, do your children need to be transported somewhere other than home (i.e., daycare) during the school year? If so, please notify the Marcellus Central School District Transportation Department as soon as possible by filling out a student transportation information form on the district website.

post_text: Looking for the school building offices? If you have a student in grades K-3, the main office is at the KCH Elementary School building. If you have a student in grades 4-8, the main offices are back at Driver Middle School. And if you're the parent of a student in grades 9-12, the main office is back at the high school. Enter through the trophy case entrance until the main entrance is complete. (All the office phone numbers are the same!)
